1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,380
I  was  left  at  the  altar  in  front  of  the  entire  town.  My

2
00:00:03,380 --> 00:00:05,640
fiance  vanished.  The  guests  laughed

3
00:00:05,640 --> 00:00:08,700
behind  my  back,  and  the  wedding  debt  fell  on  me  like  a

4
00:00:08,700 --> 00:00:11,560
sentence.  Within  days,  I  lost  my  job,

5
00:00:11,860 --> 00:00:15,220
my  home,  and  what  little  dignity  I  had  left.  That

6
00:00:15,220 --> 00:00:18,020
was  when  Ludovico  Caracolo  appeared.  The  most

7
00:00:18,020 --> 00:00:21,100
feared  man  in  Providence  offered  me  away  out.  He'd  pay

8
00:00:21,100 --> 00:00:24,400
everything.  Clear  my  name,  and  protect  me.

9
00:00:24,620 --> 00:00:27,780
If  I  agreed  to  be  his  wife  on  paper,  I  thought  I  was  entering

10
00:00:27,780 --> 00:00:29,780
a  cold  contract.  But  soon  I

11
00:00:29,780 --> 00:00:32,840
discovered  my  fiance  hadn't  just  run  away.  And  that

12
00:00:32,840 --> 00:00:35,240
Ludovico  knew  far  more  than  he  let  on.

13
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:38,560
The  bouquet  trembled  in  my  hand,  and  I  couldn't  decide

14
00:00:38,560 --> 00:00:40,160
whether  it  was  the  weight  of  the  roses,

15
00:00:40,720 --> 00:00:43,740
or  the  weight  of  the  waiting.  Providence  church  smelled  of

16
00:00:43,740 --> 00:00:45,500
melted  wax  and  old  lilies.

17
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:49,060
That  two  sweet  perfume  that  clung  to  the  throat.  The

18
00:00:49,060 --> 00:00:51,240
priest  had  already  checked  the  clock  three  times.

19
00:00:51,740 --> 00:00:54,800
The  first  time,  he  smiled  at  me  the  way  you  tried  to  calm

20
00:00:54,800 --> 00:00:57,680
a  child.  The  second.  He  turned  his  face  to

21
00:00:57,680 --> 00:01:00,780
void  my  eyes.  The  third.  He  didn't  even  bother

22
00:01:00,780 --> 00:01:03,480
pretending  anymore.  All  of  Providence  was  seated

23
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:09,140
behind me. I felt the murmur rise up the back of my white dress like a cold current, a whisper

24
00:01:09,140 --> 00:01:13,980
that swelled with every passing minute. The women in the fifth row had stopped disguising their

25
00:01:13,980 --> 00:01:19,320
whispering. One of them laughed low, held back, and I heard it because I heard everything in that

26
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:24,780
moment. The rest of the fans, the shuffle of feet, the tick talk of the old clock at the back

27
00:01:24,780 --> 00:01:30,400
of the nave. A delmo had set the time for 11 o'clock. It was ten to noon. Narina was right

28
00:01:30,400 --> 00:01:35,560
behind me. In the first row, squeezing the back of my hand as if she could hold me in place by

29
00:01:35,560 --> 00:01:40,380
the strength of her fingers. She didn't say anything. Narina had a comment for everything.

30
00:01:40,900 --> 00:01:46,440
A joke even at a funeral. And her silence right then was the most terrifying thing that happened

31
00:01:46,440 --> 00:01:52,800
to me that morning. I closed my eyes. Took a deep breath, counted to ten. I opened my eyes,

32
00:01:52,800 --> 00:01:57,780
and the church door was still empty. I, Alanda, Narina murmured close to my ear.

33
00:01:58,140 --> 00:02:04,840
Sweetheart, don't talk. My voice came out steady. Low, but steady. If you talk, I'll fall apart.

34
00:02:05,300 --> 00:02:11,540
She squeezed my hand again, and the bell began. One toll, noon, two tolls. The priest came down

35
00:02:11,540 --> 00:02:16,600
from the altar and walked over to me. Three tolls. The women in the fifth row were no longer laughing.

36
00:02:16,600 --> 00:02:24,320
Four tolls. Five, six, eleven, twelve. The bell told for the last time. And the echo hung in

37
00:02:24,320 --> 00:02:30,740
the church's vaulted ceiling like something dirty, ugly to look at. No one moved, no one coughed.

38
00:02:31,060 --> 00:02:36,300
All of Providence held its breath at the same time. And I felt in my shoulders the exact moment

39
00:02:36,300 --> 00:02:42,200
the town understood collectively that I had been abandoned. The priest stopped in front of me,

40
00:02:42,200 --> 00:02:48,000
hands folded. There was pity in his eyes. And pity is the one thing a bride doesn't know where to put.

41
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:54,860
My child? No. I clutched the bouquet to my chest. You don't have to say anything. I turned my back

42
00:02:54,860 --> 00:03:00,220
on him. Facing the altar was easier than facing Providence, but the church had only one way out.

43
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:05,360
And that way passed by every familiar face. Every stare from those who had come to see exactly

44
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:10,380
what they were now seeing. Narina stood up with me. I'm coming with you. She said,

45
00:03:10,380 --> 00:03:17,360
one step at a time. I started walking. One step. Then another. The dress dragged behind me.

46
00:03:17,640 --> 00:03:22,300
And every inch of that fabric weighed like a remnant of what I had imagined that morning would be.

47
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:27,980
I had imagined laughter. I had imagined a shy kiss at the altar. I had imagined a delmo

48
00:03:27,980 --> 00:03:35,240
squeezing my elbow with that nervous way of his whispering, I'm here, I'm here. A delmo hadn't come.

49
00:03:35,240 --> 00:03:41,600
I passed the third row. Mrs. Marchetti, my neighbor for 10 years, lowered her head. I passed the

50
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:47,200
fifth row, and no one was laughing anymore. I passed the distant cousin a delmo had invited at the last

51
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:52,140
minute, and he avoided my eyes with a haste that almost broke me. Narina held my arm.

52
00:03:52,640 --> 00:03:58,800
Look ahead. Just ahead. We reached the door. The sunlight outside hit my eyes. And for a moment

53
00:03:58,800 --> 00:04:04,260
I saw nothing. And in that white blaze of light, I almost believed I was going to wake up from the

54
00:04:04,260 --> 00:04:10,060
whole morning that it had all been a bad last minute dream. It wasn't. I went down the stone staircase

55
00:04:10,060 --> 00:04:16,180
slowly because going down fast was admitting that I wanted to run, and I had decided without

56
00:04:16,180 --> 00:04:22,920
deciding that providence would not see me run. The stones were worn in the middle. The iron railing

57
00:04:22,920 --> 00:04:28,320
darkened by age. Each step caused the same effort as a breath. A yellow taxi stopped at the bottom.

58
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:34,940
At the corner of the square. I hadn't called it. Narina had. I got in. She got in after me.

59
00:04:35,240 --> 00:04:40,840
Federal Hill, she told the driver. End of at wells near Salve's bakery. The driver looked at me

60
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:46,820
in the rear view mirror. Saw the white dress. Saw my face and didn't ask anything. He started the car

61
00:04:46,820 --> 00:04:53,060
in silence. I rested my forehead against the glass. The city rushed past outside. The statue in the

62
00:04:53,060 --> 00:04:58,380
square. Old Salve's bakery. The corner where Adelmo had kissed me for the first time three years

63
00:04:58,380 --> 00:05:03,560
ago. On that corner, he had told me he would love me until the day the world forgot how to turn.

64
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:09,140
The world had turned just fine that morning. I got home before I felt my feet. Narina opened

65
00:05:09,140 --> 00:05:14,540
the door to my apartment. Went in first. Started turning on lights. I stood in the middle of the

66
00:05:14,540 --> 00:05:20,080
living room, still in the dress, still holding the bouquet, and looked around like someone visiting a

67
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:25,920
stranger's house. Everything was still in place. The cup I had washed before leaving. The book left

68
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:32,740
open on the arm of the sofa. The empty vase waiting for the wedding flowers. I sat on the floor. I just sat.

69
00:05:33,280 --> 00:05:37,920
The dress billowed around me like a cloud. And I didn't cry because crying was asking too much

70
00:05:37,920 --> 00:05:43,260
of the body at that hour. I just sat there with the bouquet in my lap and stared at the door.

71
00:05:43,640 --> 00:05:49,120
Narina sat down next to me on the floor. Without taking off her shoes, without smoothing her dress.

72
00:05:49,120 --> 00:05:55,520
She rested her head on my shoulder and stayed. He'll show up. I said, something happened. An accident.

73
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:02,300
Something. Narina didn't answer. Narina. No. What do you mean no? He's not going to show up

74
00:06:02,300 --> 00:06:07,460
Iolanda. She lifted her head and looked me in the eye. If it had been an accident, someone would have

75
00:06:07,460 --> 00:06:13,460
called. If something had happened. His family would be at the church. No one was there. No one.

76
00:06:13,860 --> 00:06:18,540
I stayed quiet. She was right. That morning none of the reachy's had shown up.

77
00:06:18,540 --> 00:06:24,420
Not his mother. Not his brother. No one. I had seen it. And I hadn't seen it.

78
00:06:24,700 --> 00:06:29,740
Sunday passed without my remembering it. Monday morning the phone rang. The principle of the

79
00:06:29,740 --> 00:06:35,200
school where I'd been teaching literature for four years called me by my full surname with a strange

80
00:06:35,200 --> 00:06:41,860
formality. And I already knew before she finished the sentence. Iolanda, it's not a good time to

81
00:06:41,860 --> 00:06:48,900
keep a teacher involved in scandal. Scandal? I leaned against the kitchen wall. I was jilted Mrs.

82
00:06:49,100 --> 00:06:54,720
Peretti. I wasn't caught stealing. Silence on the other end. Then the mothers are talking.

83
00:06:55,360 --> 00:07:02,440
You understand? A teacher needs an intact reputation. Reputation. I repeated. The reputation of a woman

84
00:07:02,440 --> 00:07:08,060
who was humiliated in public is the reputation she lost. Iolanda, please. Please. I said,

85
00:07:08,060 --> 00:07:15,160
yes, please. I hung up. I stood in the kitchen. My hand still on the phone and felt nothing.

86
00:07:15,700 --> 00:07:22,400
No anger, no shock, no tears, just a very polite emptiness. Like the emptiness of a room after the

87
00:07:22,400 --> 00:07:28,340
guests have gone. Tuesday morning the collectors began. The first one showed up at eight in a dress shirt

88
00:07:28,340 --> 00:07:34,320
and carrying a black briefcase and said my name over the intercom with a casualness that froze my blood.

89
00:07:34,320 --> 00:07:39,980
He came up. Sat in my living room like someone who'd been there before. Open the briefcase and

90
00:07:39,980 --> 00:07:46,480
handed me a paper. You signed here. His finger stopped beneath my signature. Next to a delmo's.

91
00:07:46,860 --> 00:07:54,860
Wedding paid for with borrowed money. $12,000. Do in 30 days. I didn't sign any loan. He turned the

92
00:07:54,860 --> 00:08:01,060
paper  toward  me.  It  was  my  handwriting.  It  was  my  signature.  It  was  right  there.  Beneath  a  line

93
00:08:01,060 --> 00:08:04,300
of

94
00:08:04,300 --> 00:08:09,960
I looked closely. The signature had been collected in the pile. Along with the ceremony paperwork.

95
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:15,900
The day a delmo asked me to sign just some boring forms. Love from the venue. I had signed

96
00:08:15,900 --> 00:08:22,980
without reading. The man waited for me to understand. When I did, he closed the briefcase. You have 30 days.

97
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:28,240
If you'd rather pay an installments there's interest. If you'd rather negotiate, there are partners.

98
00:08:28,800 --> 00:08:35,260
Take your pick. He stood up. We're watching. He left. I didn't move for a stretch of time. I can't measure.

99
00:08:35,840 --> 00:08:40,760
Then I went to the window and saw his car parked across the street. I kept watching. He didn't look

100
00:08:40,760 --> 00:08:47,040
up. He didn't need to. He had already looked at me enough. That afternoon, the second man showed up.

101
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:52,280
Wednesday morning the third. Thursday morning, the eviction noticed taped to the apartment door.

102
00:08:52,620 --> 00:08:57,880
Narina arrived that night with a grocery bag and the serious face she almost never wore. She

103
00:08:57,880 --> 00:09:03,900
set the bag on the table. Pulled out a bottle of wine. Pulled out a butter knife. I brought wine and a

104
00:09:03,900 --> 00:09:10,720
butter knife. She said, pick first. I laughed before I realized I was laughing. It was an ugly laugh,

105
00:09:11,020 --> 00:09:16,900
short, lasting a second. But it was a laugh. And Narina recognized it the way you recognize a friend's

106
00:09:16,900 --> 00:09:23,520
voice after years. Butter knife. I answered. I can't handle wine tonight. She set the wine aside.

107
00:09:23,520 --> 00:09:31,340
Set down. Took off her shoes. Do you have anywhere to go? No. Do you have money? No. Do you have a plan?

108
00:09:31,900 --> 00:09:36,340
Narina? If I had a plan, I wouldn't be holding a butter knife. She squeezed my arm.

109
00:09:36,660 --> 00:09:42,840
Stayed like that for a while. You're staying with me. She said, as long as you need. My couch is ugly,

110
00:09:42,920 --> 00:09:49,200
but it's mine. I nodded slowly. I didn't know if I was thanking her or refusing. Both things at once

111
00:09:49,200 --> 00:09:55,520
maybe. She stayed late. Cooked pasta with whatever was in the pantry. Made me eat three forkables.

112
00:09:56,140 --> 00:10:00,520
Took the wedding dress off the hanger where it had hung since Saturday and carried it away without

113
00:10:00,520 --> 00:10:07,160
asking me. Tomorrow I'll burn it. She set it the door or donated to charity. You decide later.

114
00:10:07,760 --> 00:10:13,720
I decided later. E. Wednesday morning and envelope arrived. It was on the floor by the door when I

115
00:10:13,720 --> 00:10:18,760
went down to get the newspaper out of habit. Not because I wanted to read the news, but because

116
00:10:18,760 --> 00:10:23,900
going down the stairs was the only gesture of the day that still felt like mine. The envelope was

117
00:10:23,900 --> 00:10:30,900
of thick paper, the color of old cream, no stamp, no postmark, just my name written in the center,

118
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:38,380
in firm tall handwriting, slightly slanted to the right, Yolanda Marcecano, no one wrote my full name

119
00:10:38,380 --> 00:10:44,080
like  that.  Not  even  my  father  wrote  my  full  name  like  that  when  he  was  still  alive.  I  went  up

120
00:10:44,080 --> 00:10:48,740
the

121
00:10:48,740 --> 00:10:54,440
seat of something might escape from inside it. There was only a card, Cafe Veccia Roma, tomorrow,

122
00:10:55,060 --> 00:11:01,980
5pm. Perhaps I have a solution for you. L.C. I stared at the three letters. L.C. Two

123
00:11:01,980 --> 00:11:06,980
initials and a period at the end, like someone who economizes even with letters. Providence

124
00:11:06,980 --> 00:11:12,080
had three ways of pronouncing those initials and all three meant the same person. Ludovico

125
00:11:12,080 --> 00:11:17,300
Karacholo. The man the whole town bowed its head to. The man my father had forbidden me to

126
00:11:17,300 --> 00:11:22,160
look at when I was a child and saw a procession of black cars passing down at Wells Avenue.

127
00:11:22,840 --> 00:11:27,980
Don't look, Yolanda. He had said, that car in the middle is the car we pretend doesn't exist.

128
00:11:28,580 --> 00:11:34,880
I was little and I looked anyway. I saw no one. The glass was too dark. Now that same man had

129
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:40,620
written my name with his own hand. He knew my address. He knew of my shame. He knew of my debt.

130
00:11:40,920 --> 00:11:45,880
He probably knew more things about me than my ex-fiancey new. I set the card down on the table.

131
00:11:45,880 --> 00:11:53,380
I ran my finger slowly over the L. The ink still smelled almost, almost, or maybe it was my

132
00:11:53,380 --> 00:11:59,600
imagination, picturing that fresh ink as a way of him being closer. I closed my eyes. I thought

133
00:11:59,600 --> 00:12:04,120
of the eviction noticed taped to the door. I thought of the man with a black briefcase watching

134
00:12:04,120 --> 00:12:09,420
my building from across the street. I thought of Mrs. Pairetti calling me miss with disgust.

135
00:12:09,720 --> 00:12:15,300
I thought of Nareena on her ugly couch and how much she deserved to sleep in peace without a

136
00:12:15,300 --> 00:12:21,540
friend breathing in her living room. I opened my eyes. I didn't go to the cafe because I wanted to.

137
00:12:21,820 --> 00:12:27,560
I went because I had nowhere left to run. Cafe Vichia Roma sat on a corner of the old neighborhood where

138
00:12:27,560 --> 00:12:33,920
time had decided, at some point, to stop passing. Dark wooden doors, smoked glass windows.

139
00:12:34,580 --> 00:12:39,740
A discreet bell that rang when I pushed the door open, and the noise inside dropped. It didn't

140
00:12:39,740 --> 00:12:44,840
drop because of me. All the stairs at the table shifted. In a small synchronized movement,

141
00:12:45,360 --> 00:12:50,700
toward the table at the back, and the table at the back had a man sitting at it. Lutavico Caracciolo

142
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:56,840
was dressed in dark from shoulders to shoes. A suit cut with precision. A white shirt open at the

143
00:12:56,840 --> 00:13:03,260
top button, no tie. A cup of coffee resting in his right hand. His wrist exposed. An old watch

144
00:13:03,260 --> 00:13:08,940
with a worn strap. He raised his eyes when the bell rang, and saw me before I decided what to do with

145
00:13:08,940 --> 00:13:15,580
my feet. Dark hair combed back. Two days' worth of stubble. His eyes were the worst. Eyes that

146
00:13:15,580 --> 00:13:20,860
already knew of me before I arrived. As if he had memorized my face before I even reached the door.

147
00:13:21,260 --> 00:13:26,920
I walked to the table. He didn't stand. He didn't pull out the chair. He just watched me come,

148
00:13:27,200 --> 00:13:33,260
and the whole cafe watched me come with him. I sat. Miss Marcicano. His voice was low.

149
00:13:33,260 --> 00:13:39,100
Deeper than I had expected. Words spaced out. Like someone choosing them one at a time and giving

150
00:13:39,100 --> 00:13:45,760
up on the ones he didn't need. Mr. Caracciolo. I set my purse on my lap. You know all of Providence

151
00:13:45,760 --> 00:13:51,180
is looking at this table. All of Providence looks at any table I sit at. He brought the cup to his

152
00:13:51,180 --> 00:13:58,020
lips. Took a small sip. It's not about you. What a relief. The corner of his mouth twitched slightly.

153
00:13:58,620 --> 00:14:03,180
It wasn't a smile. It was the sketch of a thought he decided not to finish. A waiter

154
00:14:03,180 --> 00:14:08,640
appeared hand behind his back. Bent enough to be respectful. What will you have, ma'am? Coffee.

155
00:14:09,160 --> 00:14:15,860
Black. No sugar today. The waiter nodded and disappeared. Lutavico watched me order. He didn't say anything.

156
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:21,780
You called for me. I straightened my shoulders. I'm here. If you have something to say, say it.

157
00:14:22,080 --> 00:14:27,320
You don't like preamble. I don't have time for preamble. He set the cup down slowly on the saucer.

158
00:14:27,800 --> 00:14:32,940
The clink of porcelain was the only sound at the table for a moment. You owe $12,000 to the

159
00:14:32,940 --> 00:14:39,180
Stanzo Brothers. He said, neighborhood loan-sharking. You lost your job on Monday. You lost your

160
00:14:39,180 --> 00:14:43,880
apartment on Wednesday. You have a friend who offered you her couch. You have no living

161
00:14:43,880 --> 00:14:50,840
relatives and providence. And the fiancee, enough I cut in. You've made your point. He stopped.

162
00:14:51,340 --> 00:14:55,700
Tilted his head a fraction of a millimeter in a gesture that was almost a thank you for my

163
00:14:55,700 --> 00:15:01,980
frankness. I was going to say he continued that the fiancee is a matter you still don't understand.

164
00:15:01,980 --> 00:15:06,440
But today isn't the day for that conversation. And what day is that conversation?

165
00:15:07,080 --> 00:15:11,580
A day that depends on what you do in the next five minutes. The waiter returned with my coffee.

166
00:15:12,080 --> 00:15:17,440
I took a sip too quickly and burned my tongue on purpose to have a physical reason to pay attention.

167
00:15:17,980 --> 00:15:24,160
And say it. I said, Lutavico rested his elbow on the table. The old watch gleamed in the low light.

168
00:15:24,600 --> 00:15:31,480
I erase every scent of your debt. I buy the Costanzo's papers tonight. I give you back the

169
00:15:31,480 --> 00:15:36,940
range another one. I handle the school problem. Mrs. Peretti will get a phone call and remember

170
00:15:36,940 --> 00:15:41,480
that she likes you. You're describing a miracle. I'm describing a transaction.

171
00:15:42,160 --> 00:15:48,100
His eyes didn't waver. In exchange for a single thing. I took another sip. I didn't let my hand

172
00:15:48,100 --> 00:15:54,860
tremble. What thing? You marry me. On paper, the cafe kept making coffee around me. The steam

173
00:15:54,860 --> 00:15:59,820
wand cut through the air. Someone laughed at a distant table. And I sat there listening to the

174
00:15:59,820 --> 00:16:04,480
feared man in Providence offering me a contract marriage with the same calm you'd order the check.

175
00:16:04,960 --> 00:16:11,020
Is that a marriage proposal? I said slowly. Or a purchase order. He almost smiled. Again,

176
00:16:11,460 --> 00:16:17,120
he didn't smile. It's a proposal. You can refuse. You can get up from this table right now.

177
00:16:17,340 --> 00:16:22,620
And the only thing I'll do is pay for your coffee. And tomorrow? Tomorrow the Costanzo brothers still

178
00:16:22,620 --> 00:16:27,440
exist. And the eviction notice is still taped to the door. I held the cup more firmly.

179
00:16:27,440 --> 00:16:33,100
Marriage on paper, I repeated. What does that mean exactly? A civil contract?

180
00:16:33,820 --> 00:16:38,280
City Hall. No religious ceremony. He began counting the rules on his fingers.

181
00:16:38,780 --> 00:16:44,680
Without lifting his hand from the table, just moving them one by one. You live in my house. You have your own

182
00:16:44,680 --> 00:16:51,880
room. I have another. Both doors stay closed. Go on. In public, you're my wife. You go to events with me.

183
00:16:52,140 --> 00:16:56,300
You smile when it's time to smile. You don't need to pretend more than that.

184
00:16:56,300 --> 00:17:02,920
In private, nothing. I won't touch you. I won't go into your room. I won't ask about your life.

185
00:17:03,280 --> 00:17:08,880
And you won't ask about mine. No questions. No questions. I set the cup on the saucer.

186
00:17:09,360 --> 00:17:14,160
I thought that no questions had the smell of a locked door. And locked doors were exactly the

187
00:17:14,160 --> 00:17:20,240
ones I always wanted to open. For how long? One year. After that, you can ask for the separation

188
00:17:20,240 --> 00:17:26,020
without any contest from me. If you'd rather stay longer, it's negotiable. Why me? It was the first

189
00:17:26,020 --> 00:17:31,300
question of mine that took him a second longer to answer. Just a second. Because you need it,

190
00:17:31,580 --> 00:17:36,360
his voice dropped half a tone. And because I need a wife for reasons that don't fit into this

191
00:17:36,360 --> 00:17:42,420
conversation, I held his gaze. He held mine. Neither of us blinked for a stretch of time that would have

192
00:17:42,420 --> 00:17:47,720
been awkward at any other table. I'll think about it. I said, you haven't till tomorrow morning.

193
00:17:48,220 --> 00:17:53,220
Me. He took from the inner pocket of his jacket, a cream-colored card with tall, firm handwriting.

194
00:17:53,220 --> 00:18:00,200
The address of a city hall. If you show up, it's yes. If you don't, it's no. I took the card.

195
00:18:00,680 --> 00:18:05,540
Our fingers didn't touch, but they passed so close that I felt the warmth of his hand for half a second

196
00:18:05,540 --> 00:18:11,700
before I pulled mine back. Do you always negotiate like this? I asked two sentences in a card?

197
00:18:12,220 --> 00:18:17,720
No. He leaned back in his chair. But with you, I didn't want to make things up. I stood up from the

198
00:18:17,720 --> 00:18:23,200
table. I didn't thank him for the coffee. He didn't expect me to. I walked to the door with my

199
00:18:23,200 --> 00:18:28,520
backstrait, knowing all of Providence would be recounting this scene for weeks. When I touched the

200
00:18:28,520 --> 00:18:35,160
handle,  I  heard  behind  me.  Low.  Almost  thought  aloud.  Two  sugar  cubes.  A  drop

201
00:18:35,160 --> 00:18:36,560
of  milk.  I  stopped.

202
00:18:37,120 --> 00:18:42,660
I looked over my shoulder. What? Ludovico didn't look at me. He was stirring his own coffee with a

203
00:18:42,660 --> 00:18:48,080
small spoon. That's how you take it. When you're not testing me, I stood there a second longer

204
00:18:48,080 --> 00:18:56,020
than I should have. Then I opened the door and left. I slept badly. I woke before the sun. I

205
00:18:56,020 --> 00:19:01,780
shoured. Put on the least wrinkled blue dress in my closet. Gathered my documents into a small bag

206
00:19:01,780 --> 00:19:06,500
and went down the stairs without saying goodbye to a single thing. I left a short note for

207
00:19:06,500 --> 00:19:11,700
Narina on the kitchen table. The kind that explains nothing and promises everything. I'd have to

208
00:19:11,700 --> 00:19:17,200
take the scolding later. City Hall was three blocks from the harbor. I arrived 15 minutes before

209
00:19:17,200 --> 00:19:24,020
he was already there. Leaning against the corridor wall. Hands in his jacket pockets. Looking at his

210
00:19:24,020 --> 00:19:29,200
own shoe like someone who'd been waiting long enough to have memorized the floor. Beside him, an

211
00:19:29,200 --> 00:19:34,400
older man, broad shouldered. But the look of someone who'd come back from wars no one had named.

212
00:19:34,920 --> 00:19:41,200
Ludovico raised his head when he saw me. He didn't smile. He made no ceremony. He just waited for me to

213
00:19:41,200 --> 00:19:47,020
arrive. Good morning. I said, good morning. He made a discreet gesture toward the man beside

214
00:19:47,760 --> 00:19:53,660
Bastion Del Rose. He works with me. He'll be nearby whenever you go out. Bastion tilted his head

215
00:19:53,660 --> 00:20:01,380
half a degree. No hello, no pleasure, no smile, just the half degree. Nice to meet you. I answered

216
00:20:01,380 --> 00:20:06,820
anyway, because my grandmother would have smacked me if I didn't answer. The clerk called us.

217
00:20:07,100 --> 00:20:12,700
We went into a small room with a long table. Papers already prepared. Ludovico pushed them toward

218
00:20:12,700 --> 00:20:18,100
me before the clerk could open his mouth. Read it, slowly. If there's any claws you don't accept,

219
00:20:18,640 --> 00:20:23,400
we redo it. I read every line. It was exactly the way he'd said in the cafe.

220
00:20:24,040 --> 00:20:31,540
Separate rooms, appearances in public, no questions, one year, right of unilateral exit on her part.

221
00:20:31,740 --> 00:20:36,880
I reached the last page and slid my finger down to the signature line. I saw nothing I wasn't supposed

222
00:20:36,880 --> 00:20:44,320
to see. Not then. It's fine. I said, I signed. He signed after me. The clerk stamped it.

223
00:20:44,520 --> 00:20:50,500
There was no kiss, no photo, no rice thrown on the way out. The three of us left City Hall in

224
00:20:50,500 --> 00:20:57,580
silence. The car was waiting. Black, glossy, glass too dark. The kind my father used to tell me

225
00:20:57,580 --> 00:21:02,920
not to look at when I was a child. Bastion opened the rear door. Ludovico got in from the other

226
00:21:02,920 --> 00:21:07,760
side and sat next to me without saying anything. The car took the road toward the upper suburb.

227
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:13,480
Providence shrank in the window. The red rooftops falling away behind us. In green took over.

228
00:21:13,960 --> 00:21:19,060
He didn't speak the entire way. Neither did I. The mansion gate appeared after 20 minutes.

229
00:21:19,540 --> 00:21:25,640
Dark iron, tall, with a discreet crest in the center. A lion's head with the crown split in two.

230
00:21:25,940 --> 00:21:31,520
I didn't ask what it meant. It was part of the no questions. The gate opened. The car went up a

231
00:21:31,520 --> 00:21:37,040
plane of low trees. I saw the house before I knew it was a house. Three stories of pale stone,

232
00:21:37,420 --> 00:21:43,060
tall windows, a double staircase at the entrance. A small woman, my grandmother's age,

233
00:21:43,500 --> 00:21:48,660
appeared at the door above. Her pulled into a low bun, white apron, dry hands,

234
00:21:49,380 --> 00:21:55,440
Donachyata, Ludovico said, this is Yolanda. Donachyata looked me over from head to toe,

235
00:21:55,800 --> 00:22:00,760
not with judgment, with concern. The kind of look only a kitchen woman knows how to give.

236
00:22:00,760 --> 00:22:06,940
Welcome. She said, you must be tired. I'm fine. She didn't believe me, but she

237
00:22:06,940 --> 00:22:11,920
not did and didn't insist. Ludovico took me upstairs. The upper corridor was long,

238
00:22:12,260 --> 00:22:17,060
with identical doors on both sides. He stopped at the third door on the right and opened it.

239
00:22:17,260 --> 00:22:23,320
This is your room. It was too big for one person. A canopy double bed, a desk at the window,

240
00:22:23,920 --> 00:22:29,520
a built-in closet, a long and entire wall. Everything in shades of cream and gray, a tasteful

241
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:34,560
My room is at the end of the corridor. He said, behind me, on the left side,

242
00:22:34,940 --> 00:22:40,520
you don't need to go past it. Understood? If you need anything, Donachyata is always nearby.

243
00:22:41,180 --> 00:22:47,760
And you, he paused a second. If you need me, Donachyata knows where I am. I turned to look at him.

244
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:52,700
He was standing in the doorway, one hand on the handle, looking at some point between my shoulder

245
00:22:52,700 --> 00:22:57,800
and the window. For the first time since the cafe, he seemed unsure of where to put his gaze.

246
00:22:57,800 --> 00:23:03,620
Thank you. I said, I wasn't quite sure why. He tilted his head a fraction of a millimeter,

247
00:23:04,280 --> 00:23:10,160
closed the door. I heard his footsteps go down the corridor, and silence. I sat on the edge of the bed.

248
00:23:10,620 --> 00:23:14,800
I ran my hand over the duvet, and the fabric was soft in a way that made my eyes sting

249
00:23:14,800 --> 00:23:20,920
without warning. I didn't cry. Not that first afternoon. That night, Donachyata came up with a

250
00:23:20,920 --> 00:23:27,380
tray, hot soup, fresh bread, a glass of red wine. I didn't ask her to swap it for water. I

251
00:23:27,380 --> 00:23:31,920
drank the wine to the last drop. I laid down without changing my clothes and stared at the ceiling

252
00:23:31,920 --> 00:23:38,920
of the canopy. Near midnight, I heard footsteps in the corridor, slow, measured footsteps. They came

253
00:23:38,920 --> 00:23:44,060
from the end of the corridor. They reached my door. They stopped. They stood there for a stretch of

254
00:23:44,060 --> 00:23:51,020
time. I couldn't measure. Five seconds. Ten. More than ten. He didn't knock. He didn't call out.

255
00:23:51,160 --> 00:23:56,760
He made no sound. Then the footsteps went back. I heard them move away slowly. The same rhythm.

256
00:23:56,760 --> 00:24:00,860
In the direction they had come from. The door at the end of the corridor opened.

257
00:24:01,320 --> 00:24:07,200
Closed. I stared at the canopy in the same position and understood. Lying in that bed too big for

258
00:24:07,200 --> 00:24:13,080
one person. That the man the town feared had come to my door on the first night. Not to come in,

259
00:24:13,280 --> 00:24:19,620
not to speak. Only to stop outside, and then go back. I closed my eyes. I didn't sleep.

260
00:24:20,040 --> 00:24:25,080
The Karatio Lomansion woke before I did. I discovered this on the first morning. When I came

261
00:24:25,080 --> 00:24:29,880
down the marble stairs, still in my robe, fastened up to my neck, and found the house already breathing.

262
00:24:30,640 --> 00:24:35,560
Donachiyara, tidying the sideboard in the hall, the smell of fresh bread coming from the kitchen.

263
00:24:36,160 --> 00:24:40,380
A staff member I didn't recognize cleaning the vestibule stained glass with silent movements.

264
00:24:40,920 --> 00:24:45,200
No one looked at me as if I didn't belong there. No one looked at me as if I belonged either.

265
00:24:45,700 --> 00:24:50,300
It was worse than hostility. It was professional neutrality. Good morning, ma'am.

266
00:24:50,940 --> 00:24:55,960
Donachiyara said, seeing me standing in the kitchen archway. Coffee here or in the garden room,

267
00:24:56,340 --> 00:25:02,180
it took me a second to understand that ma'am was me. Here is fine. I answered. If it's not in the

268
00:25:02,180 --> 00:25:07,380
way, she laughed softly. The kind of laugh only Italian women of a certain age know how to give

269
00:25:07,380 --> 00:25:12,880
without taking their hands off their apron. You, in the way in my kitchen. That's a good one.

270
00:25:13,220 --> 00:25:17,540
I sat on the wooden bench against the counter. Donachiyara said a cup in front of me without

271
00:25:17,540 --> 00:25:23,300
asking how I wanted it. Two sugar cubes had been dissolved in it. A drop of milk had been added on top.

272
00:25:23,800 --> 00:25:29,100
The coffee was exactly the color I'd been drinking since I was 15. I held the cup with both hands.

273
00:25:29,560 --> 00:25:34,480
Did you tell Mr. Ludovico? Donachiyara kept stirring a pot on the stove without turning around.

274
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:40,360
No one needed to tell me anything, my dear. Mr. Ludovico left it noted. He asked that it be this

275
00:25:40,360 --> 00:25:46,740
way every day. She paused briefly. Always. I drank the coffee too slowly. That was how the first

276
00:25:46,740 --> 00:25:52,700
week went. I'd discover a house rule by accident. And Ludovico had already altered the rule in silence.

277
00:25:52,920 --> 00:25:58,180
So I'd fit inside it. On Monday, I mentioned aloud to Donachiyara that I missed the bookside

278
00:25:58,180 --> 00:26:03,460
left in my apartment. On Tuesday, three of my favorites were on the little table in my room

279
00:26:03,460 --> 00:26:09,200
with new bookmarks between the pages. On Wednesday, I told Bastion I hated the black car because

280
00:26:09,200 --> 00:26:14,740
it reminded me of a funeral. I only said it sarcastically, because he'd appeared in a dark suit in

281
00:26:14,740 --> 00:26:20,060
corridor and I wanted to provoke him. On Thursday, Bastion appeared at the winter garden door with

282
00:26:20,060 --> 00:26:25,460
his hands folded in front of his body, with the stone face that was already his trademark. He asked

283
00:26:25,460 --> 00:26:30,140
me to ask whether you'd prefer the gray car or the black one to go out today. I looked up from

284
00:26:30,140 --> 00:26:36,200
my book. Do I have something scheduled today? You will, if you want to. You blinked once.

285
00:26:36,860 --> 00:26:42,520
Bastion, I said, trying not to laugh. Were you always like this or were you trained? Both,

286
00:26:43,020 --> 00:26:47,680
and he went back down the corridor with a step identical to the one he'd arrived with. I kept

287
00:26:47,680 --> 00:26:53,000
staring at the door for half a minute with the book forgotten in my lap, and admitted to myself that

288
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:58,240
this house was starting to become an intimate joke I had an ass to be part of. The problem was,

289
00:26:58,500 --> 00:27:04,200
the joke had an owner, and the owner of the joke didn't smile. Lutavico and I crossed paths with

290
00:27:04,200 --> 00:27:10,940
icy  formality.  In  the  corridor,  he'd  nod,  affidegree,  enough  not  to  be  rude.  At

291
00:27:10,940 --> 00:27:12,400
dinner,  we  sat  at  the

292
00:27:12,400 --> 00:27:17,320
two ends of the long table like two chess pieces pretending the board was too big for any attack.

293
00:27:17,840 --> 00:27:22,920
He'd asked if I'd needed anything. I'd answer no. He'd asked if Dona Chiara had been kind.

294
00:27:23,500 --> 00:27:29,020
I'd answer that she was an angel. He'd fold his napkin and stand up. No questions. That was

295
00:27:29,020 --> 00:27:34,660
the rule. He kept the rule better than I did. Wednesday evening, Narina showed up at the gate with

296
00:27:34,660 --> 00:27:39,140
a leather bag that looked like it weighed more than she did. Bastion opened the gate for her without

297
00:27:39,980 --> 00:27:45,560
Dona Chiara hugged her like a relative. Narina walked through the hall with wide eyes and a comment

298
00:27:45,560 --> 00:27:51,020
on the tip of her tongue. This place looks like a museum with tasteful ghosts. I pulled her into

299
00:27:51,020 --> 00:27:57,580
the kitchen before Lutavico could appear. Sweetie, she whispered, taking a Tupperware container out of her

300
00:27:57,580 --> 00:28:03,820
bag. I brought my grandmother's lasagna, not that Dona Chiara needs help, but my grandma liked you,

301
00:28:03,820 --> 00:28:09,240
and I wasn't going to let that slide. You're a social hazard. I know. Where does he sleep?

302
00:28:09,960 --> 00:28:15,640
Narina? Just so I know the distance between the two rooms, Missy. It's field research. We sat

303
00:28:15,640 --> 00:28:21,460
on the kitchen bench, split the lasagna into two bowls, and ate in secret like two teenagers who'd

304
00:28:21,460 --> 00:28:26,280
snuck out of the cafeteria. It was the first time I'd laughed since the church bell. I laughed

305
00:28:26,280 --> 00:28:33,320
for real. My face half lowered, almost choking on a piece of cheese. Dona Chiara passed by the door,

306
00:28:33,320 --> 00:28:39,880
pretended not to see, and kept going toward the garden. Lutavico passed by the door five minutes later.

307
00:28:40,320 --> 00:28:45,780
He also pretended not to see, but I saw him. He had his shirts leave rolled up to the elbow,

308
00:28:46,180 --> 00:28:51,340
his hair a little out of place. The kind of detail I shouldn't have registered. He stopped in the

309
00:28:51,340 --> 00:28:57,180
archway for half a second, exactly long enough to identify me laughing, and kept going down the corridor

310
00:28:57,180 --> 00:29:02,480
without saying anything. Narina gave me a discreet kick on the foot under the bench. Sweetie,

311
00:29:02,480 --> 00:29:07,760
she whispered. mouthful. That man just looked at you the way you look at an open window in the

312
00:29:07,760 --> 00:29:13,380
middle of winter. Shut up. It's a professional observation. You're a music teacher, Narina.

313
00:29:14,080 --> 00:29:19,980
Music is observation, my girl. What do you think we listen to? I nudged her with my elbow. She laughed.

314
00:29:20,500 --> 00:29:25,640
Dona Chiara came back with a picture of water as if nothing had happened. I took a long sip and said nothing

315
00:29:25,640 --> 00:29:31,940
more. That night, when Narina left, the corridor was too silent. I passed the library door,

316
00:29:31,940 --> 00:29:37,860
and saw the light on under the crack. I didn't go in. I went to my room, closed the door,

317
00:29:38,220 --> 00:29:43,500
and took a long time to fall asleep. The kitchen was too big for crying at dawn. I discovered

318
00:29:43,500 --> 00:29:49,440
this three days later, on Monday, when I came down barefoot at three in the morning, because I'd

319
00:29:49,440 --> 00:29:55,060
woken with my heart in my throat, and a dream of an empty church stuck to my neck. I turned on

320
00:29:55,060 --> 00:30:00,580
only the light above the stove. I sat on the cold floor with my back against the cabinet. The

321
00:30:00,580 --> 00:30:06,280
crying came without sound. The way I'd learned to cry when I lived with my grandmother, and she

322
00:30:06,280 --> 00:30:11,800
didn't like to hear sadness after ten at night. I heard the footsteps before I saw his shadow in the

323
00:30:11,800 --> 00:30:16,360
archway. He didn't turn on the main light. He stood there for two seconds in the doorway,

324
00:30:16,940 --> 00:30:22,520
in a white shirt open at the collar. His hair sang he hadn't slept either. He didn't ask anything.

325
00:30:22,860 --> 00:30:28,000
I lifted my chin before he could think of touching me. I don't need an audience to cry. Thank you.

326
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:33,880
He stopped in a very specific way, without retreating or advancing. He just stayed. Then,

327
00:30:34,080 --> 00:30:39,400
without saying a word, he crossed the kitchen, opened the cabinet beside my shoulder, and took out a

328
00:30:39,400 --> 00:30:44,260
glass. He filled the glass with water at the sink. He set the glass on the floor near my knee.

329
00:30:44,680 --> 00:30:49,980
He sat on the floor across from me. His back against the opposite cabinet, his legs stretched out

330
00:30:49,980 --> 00:30:56,080
in a way that made his feet almost touch mine, and he stayed. He didn't talk. He didn't ask.

331
00:30:56,080 --> 00:31:02,500
He didn't offer a shoulder. He stayed there. On the cold kitchen floor, with his rumpled shirt

332
00:31:02,500 --> 00:31:08,480
and his gaze on some point between my knee and the baseboard, breathing slowly. I cried for two more

333
00:31:08,480 --> 00:31:14,560
minutes. I drank half the glass. I cried a little more. I drank the rest. When I stood up,

334
00:31:15,100 --> 00:31:20,180
he stood up too, without touching me. He collected the glass, carried it to the sink,

335
00:31:20,720 --> 00:31:26,060
washed it with the same calm he did everything else. Good night, Ayolanda. I went back to my room,

336
00:31:26,060 --> 00:31:31,580
and took a long time to fall asleep again, but for another reason. The first public dinner came

337
00:31:31,580 --> 00:31:37,960
on Friday night. Iel Jira Sole, a restaurant that served all of Providence without serving anyone properly,

338
00:31:38,580 --> 00:31:44,280
with a crystal chandelier and a metre, who lowered his head half a degree when Luda Vico entered.

339
00:31:44,740 --> 00:31:50,280
He told me at breakfast with a short sentence. In the way I already recognized as his way of asking

340
00:31:50,280 --> 00:31:56,060
without asking, ill Jira Sole, nine at night. It's important that we appear together.

341
00:31:56,520 --> 00:32:02,200
Dress? Whatever you think is good, I chose the dark blue one, the one with thin straps that

342
00:32:02,200 --> 00:32:06,820
fell to mid-caf. I put on the only pair of earrings I'd brought from the old department. I

343
00:32:06,820 --> 00:32:11,140
came down the stairs with my hair pinned at the nape, and saw Luda Vico waiting below,

344
00:32:11,520 --> 00:32:15,760
in a black suit that looked like it had been cut on his body, and an expression he managed to

345
00:32:15,760 --> 00:32:18,200
keep closed for three seconds before looking away.

346
00:32:19,300 --> 00:32:26,920
Let's go, he said. At the restaurant, everyone looked, no one stared. We sat at a table near the back.

347
00:32:27,400 --> 00:32:32,280
The metre poured the wine with slightly trembling hands. Luda Vico ordered for me without consulting

348
00:32:32,280 --> 00:32:37,760
me. A dish I wouldn't have ordered, and that was exactly the way I liked it. I raised an eyebrow.

349
00:32:38,320 --> 00:32:44,340
Does Dona Ciara have a notebook of records? I asked. She has a memory. Her memory is about me,

350
00:32:44,340 --> 00:32:50,340
about everyone who sits at her table. I took a sip. Luda Vico. He looked up. Does this still

351
00:32:50,340 --> 00:32:55,500
feel more like a contract than a marriage? He held the glass by the stem, swirled the wine a quarter

352
00:32:55,500 --> 00:33:00,260
turn, set the glass back on the table without drinking. What would you rather it feel like?

353
00:33:00,660 --> 00:33:07,620
I don't know. I admitted. I'm still figuring it out. He almost smiled. Almost. It was at that

354
00:33:07,620 --> 00:33:13,200
moment that Renolfo Cerovalle crossed the restaurant. I didn't know who he was. I only felt the

355
00:33:13,200 --> 00:33:18,140
restaurant changed temperature before he reached the table. Luda Vico stiffened half a degree.

356
00:33:18,520 --> 00:33:23,860
Enough for me to notice. Not enough for anyone else to notice. Renolfo was a man in a light suit,

357
00:33:24,420 --> 00:33:29,440
a wide smile and heavy shoulders, with a colabrian accent that dragged the consonants in a strange

358
00:33:29,440 --> 00:33:36,480
way. Luda Vico, what a nice surprise. Renolfo. And this must be the new Mrs. Cerociolo.

359
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:41,860
Renolfo turned to me with theatrical courtesy and extended his hand and immense pleasure.

360
00:33:41,860 --> 00:33:47,360
Before I could decide what to do with my hand, Luda Vico simply looked at him. He didn't speak.

361
00:33:47,860 --> 00:33:52,540
He didn't move. He just looked. The look lasted exactly the length of one breath,

362
00:33:52,920 --> 00:33:57,600
and Renolfo understood. He withdrew his hand with the smile still hanging on his face,

363
00:33:57,960 --> 00:34:02,480
in the way of a man who knows he's lost this round, and that the next subject is better left

364
00:34:02,480 --> 00:34:08,040
untouched. Anyway, Renolfo said with forced lightness, good to see you Luda Vico,

365
00:34:08,040 --> 00:34:14,220
